ticism / rEllens, J. Harold -- t29. The End of History: Common Concepts in 1 Enoch and Mark / rGelardini, Gabriella -- t30. What Did the Author of Acts Know About Pre-70 Judaism? / rGrabbe, Lester L. -- t31. Sacrifice, Prayer, and the Holy Spirit: The Tamid Offering in Luke-Acts / rKinzer, Mark S. -- t32. La figura di Giovanni Battista alla luce della letteratura qumranica: alcune considerazioni / rMartone, Corrado -- t33. Being Children of Abraham: Salvation "By Belonging" in the New Testament / rNoffke, Eric -- t34. Are Luke and Acts Anti-Marcionite? / rOliver, Isaac W. -- t35. "I Have Been Born Among You": Jesus, Jews, and Christians in the Second Century / rWaddell, James -- tPart V: Ways Not Parted: Jews and Christians in Late Antiquity -- t36. The Talmudic Apocalypse: Ḥagigah, Chapter 2 / rBoyarin, Daniel -- t37. John the Baptist According to Marcion's Gospel and Early Syriac Texts / rCamplani, Alberto -- t38. Unveiling the Obvious-Synagogue and Church: Sisters or Different Species? / rPetersen, Anders Klostergaard -- t39. Christian Paideia and the Politics of Empire in Eunapius' Vitae Sophistarum / rvon Ehrenkrook, Jason -- tList of Contributors  aThis collection presents innovative research by scholars from across the globe in celebration of Gabriele Boccaccini's sixtieth birthday and to honor his contribution to the study of early Judaism and Christianity. In harmony with Boccaccini's determination to promote the study of Second Temple Judaism in its own right, this volume includes studies on various issues raised in early Jewish apocalyptic literature (e.g., 1 Enoch, 2 Baruch, 4 Ezra), the Dead Sea Scrolls, and other early Jewish texts, from Tobit to Ben Sira to Philo and beyond. The volume also provides several investigations on early Christianity in intimate conversation with its Jewish sources, consistent with Boccaccini's efforts to transcend confessional and disciplinary divisions by situating the origins of Christianity firmly within Second Temple Judaism. Finally, the volume includes essays that look at Jewish-Christian relations in the centuries following the Second Temple period, a harvest of Boccaccini's labor to rethink the relationship between Judaism and Christianity in light of their shared yet contested heritage.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Nov 2018) 0aApocalyptic literature. 0aChristian literature, Early. 0aHebrew literature. 0aJewish literature. 4aEnoch. 4aHenoch. 4aJewish-Christian relations. 4aJüdisch-Christliches Verhältnis. 4aNeues Testament. 4aNew Testament. 4aSecond Temple Judaism. 4aZweiter Tempel.1 aEllens, J. Harold, eeditor.1 aOliver, Isaac W., eeditor.1 aWaddell, James, eeditor.1 aZurawski, Jason M., eeditor.1 avon Ehrenkrook, Jason, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2018 Englishz978311060424508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2018z9783110603248oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831105937920 cprintz978311059588840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110596717423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110596717.jpg  a978-3-11-060424-5  EBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGFb201